<font color="#FF0000">...MINDS AND HEARTS...THE WALL</font><br>
<tt>Tue Dec  3 23:08:57 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
We all came back from that war with our own wounds...some have learned to deal with it, some are still fighting the battles. But for me, the war is over! I've learned to put it in perspective. Yet, it is and will forever be apart of my<br>
life. There are times I awake in a sweat, shaking from what I know, what I saw, what I did...but it is only a dream <br>
[nightmare], that's behind me now!<br><br>
In front of me is a poster of 'the wall&quot;, with 2 rubbings,<br>
Edward F. Brady III...Myllin G. Henrich...friends, comrades,<br>
memories.It all came into focus when I went to the VN Veterans Memorial. <br><br>
First at the dedication in '82, and many times since, but each time I came away with a new perspective. At first it invoked intense emotion, pain that was once hidden was now felt again. I now know it was needed, I needed to make peace with myself. Soon, as those emotions were delt with, I began to feel a sense of accomplishment. Once again, Vietnam Vets took to their own ranks to find the strength and courage to establish their place in history. The Wall is a starting point, a foundation on which to build , and move on from. <br><br>
Then along with that came pride. Proud to have served in Vietnam, to have served when my country called; and equally proud of all Vets who served their country when called. And no greater pride than for those who sacrificed all. <br><br>
When I return to the Memorial, be sure it will still hurt...<br>
but it will be a pain born from a sense of accomplishment, a feeling of pride, with the knowledge that we are united again, in our minds and hearts.<br><br>
As much as Veterans Day is observed as a day to remember our fallen comrades, so is it a day to reaffirm our commitment and dedication to ALL Veterans.  <br><br>
rkp<br>
Vietnam Veteran
